{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/big-data-and-sketchy-algorithms-3e4d850e1a82", "time": 1683017262.330715, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/big-data-and-sketchy-algorithms-3e4d850e1a82/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Big Data and Sketchy algorithms. The art and science of data stream\u2026 | by Dimitris Poulopoulos | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Big Data and Sketchy algorithms", "description": "The art and science of data stream summary is a sketchy business."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://mailchi.mp/d2d2d4a109b5/learning-rate-newsletter", "anchor_text": "Learning Rate", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://mailchi.mp/d2d2d4a109b5/learning-rate-newsletter", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://users-cs.au.dk/~gerth/madalgo/old-madalgo.au.dk/img/SumSchoo2007_Lecture%20slides/Bibliography/p14_Cormode_JAl_05.pdf", "anchor_text": "Graham Cormode and S. Muthu Muthukrishnan in 2003", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/AWNystrom/CountMinSketch", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://github.com/AWNystrom", "anchor_text": "Andrew Nystrom", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/dpoulopoulos/", "anchor_text": "Dimitris Poulopoulos", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://www.arrikto.com/", "anchor_text": "Arrikto", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/medium.com/@dpoulopoulos/follow", "anchor_text": "Medium", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/dpoulopoulos/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/james2pl", "anchor_text": "@james2pl", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "http://www.dimpo.me", "anchor_text": "www.dimpo.me", "paragraph_index": 20}], "all_paragraphs": ["Imagine running a poll, and the whole world is participating. The survey has no fixed answers. Anyone can write down their favorite word or phrase and, in the end, you want to announce the most beloved concept. It follows that the possible replies are nearly infinite.", "Thus, the first naive way to store the votes cast for every word in a hash-table is inefficient. You want a structure that takes sub-linear space to store the number of occurrences for each term. In this story, we look at a probabilistic data structure, called count-min sketch.", "In the first section, we explain what count-min sketch is and how to use it. Then, we consider the unavoidable trade-offs, its advantages, and disadvantages and a piece of final advice on when to use it.", "Learning Rate is a newsletter for those who are curious about the world of AI and MLOps. You\u2019ll hear from me every Friday with updates and thoughts on the latest AI news and articles. Subscribe here!", "Count-min sketch uses several hash functions that assign any value to a predefined number of buckets. Thus, we can depict it as a matrix, where the rows are the hash functions, and the columns signify the buckets.", "In the beginning, we initialize the table with zeros. Then, the methodology, in our case, can be described by the following simple steps.", "2. Increment the values in the corresponding columns. For example, for the word \u201cmother\u201d we increment the values of columns 2, 1, 1, 4, for the corresponding hash function:", "3. Repeat steps 1 and 2 for every word. For instance, if our next word is \u201clove\u201d we might get:", "Hence, the resulting table is given below:", "4. To get the count for any item, we first compute each function's value, retrieve the count according to the results, and report the minimum value. For example, to get the count of the word \u201cmother\u201d we follow the steps below:", "This straightforward algorithm invented by Graham Cormode and S. Muthu Muthukrishnan in 2003 produces great results for a fraction of hash-table memory.", "Many implementations of count-min sketch exist already. You can go through a pure python example here, by Andrew Nystrom.", "One property of count-min sketch is that it can overestimate but never underestimate occurrences. This can be mitigated by employing more hash functions to minimize collisions at the expense of memory. Thus, count-min sketch is a poor fit for applications that demand an exact count of events.", "On the other hand, we do not need to allocate more memory when adding a new item to the set. Thus, memory consumption remains constant, as we only increment counters (i.e., integer values). Moreover, count-min sketch is parallelizable if we rarely have collisions, which means that we may need a \u201ctaller\u201d table (i.e., more hash functions).", "This story examines the count-min sketch algorithm, how it works, and when we should use it. We discuss some of its trade-offs, advantages, and disadvantages.", "The key takeaway is that count-min sketch is a data structure that takes sub-linear space to store the number of occurrences for each term. Whenever you have an application that does not require absolute precision, count-min sketch is a great method to keep memory consumption under control.", "My name is Dimitris Poulopoulos, and I\u2019m a machine learning engineer working for Arrikto. I have designed and implemented AI and software solutions for major clients such as the European Commission, Eurostat, IMF, the European Central Bank, OECD, and IKEA.", "If you are interested in reading more posts about Machine Learning, Deep Learning, Data Science, and DataOps, follow me on Medium, LinkedIn, or @james2pl on Twitter.", "Opinions expressed are solely my own and do not express the views or opinions of my employer.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Machine Learning Engineer. I talk about AI, MLOps, and Python programming. More about me: www.dimpo.me"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F3e4d850e1a82&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&s